In the time of epidemic crisis, we should reflect that we should strengthen the reform of household registration system and the process of citizenization to solve the social problems caused by large-scale population flow

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Figure / Fachen

By Li Tie

The biggest challenge facing the COVID-19 in its nationwide battle against swine flu is the issue of transmissibility. For Wuhan, the city with the most severe outbreak, there are two inescapable facts. One is that about 5 million people from outside the city have left, most of whom are migrant workers. The other is that it is during the Spring Festival, at the height of the homecoming season and the post-holiday rush.

This shows that China's special situation of population mobility, is an important reason for the intensification of the epidemic risk.

The risks of massive population movements

We should also note that Wuhan has about 15 million people under management, 11 million residents and 9.06 million registered residents. In this way, we will be faced with three dimensions of demographic data, population management, resident population and registered population. Of particular note is the managed population, which in many cities tends to exceed the resident population. Shenzhen, for example, has a registered population of about 5M, a resident population of more than 13m and a purported management population of more than 20m.

Based on the above data, it is clear that the real pressure on mobility is not the registered population, but all the migrant population.

The annual Spring Festival travel rush, the peak of China's migration, is also among the largest in the world. During the 40 days or so of migration and migration, the Spring Festival travel rush was faced only with a severe shortage of transportation infrastructure. But should any outbreak occur during this period, a large-scale movement of people would put enormous pressure not only on the affected areas, but also on virtually all urban and rural areas of the country.

According to figures released on January 26 in Wuhan, more than five million people have left the city because of the Spring Festival and the outbreak. The vast majority of these 5 million people are returning home for the Spring Festival. They will return to their hometowns, where they are registered and where their parents live, and their hometowns are scattered across the country, creating a national panic. Judging from the spread of the epidemic situation, it has also triggered a chain reaction in various places.

Population Movement will not only cause the spread of the new coronavirus epidemic across the country, through the large-scale return to the city after the Spring Festival, but also may trigger a new epidemic crisis.

Because of the large-scale floating population of employment characteristics, making China's epidemic prevention and control pressure far more than any other country. It is understandable that, in this situation, the adoption of a national mobilization approach to prevent the spread of the epidemic, the various measures have their place. Fortunately, China has the strongest institutional mobilization force in the world. We not only have a sound system of governance of social organizations, but also use the available scientific and technological means to take the most effective way to carry out general mobilization against epidemic diseases.

However, it is important to note that the economic and social costs of facing the pressure of huge population movements are also enormous.

By 2019, China's total population had reached 1.4 billion, of which only 600 million were registered as urban residents and 280 million were included in the permanent urban population statistics, of which 170 million were migrant workers. In addition, the so-called management of the population of tourism, family visits, travel and other reasons of the floating population, together with 80 million between the urban migrant employment population, the total number of floating population may be more than 300 million.

For Wuhan, the migrant population during the Spring Festival is about 5 million, but for Hubei Province, the migrant population will be more than 5 million. It was this mobility that led to the spread of the epidemic from Wuhan to the whole country.

Because of the scale of the effort, it is not yet possible to calculate the economic cost of the epidemic, which some studies say could be in the trillions.

The more serious problem is that a large number of small and medium-sized service enterprises are facing a serious crisis. Whether it is urban services, tourism, which is just on the rise, or all related industries, which are going through periods of closure that can last as long as a month, the financial and cost pressures are simply too much to bear. In addition, the government at all levels for the epidemic prevention and control of financial costs, including human, material and other resources expenditure, will be a huge number. Moreover, an extension of the outbreak is likely to have an impact on international economic exchanges and trade, and is a major risk that may be faced.

While we have the capacity to mobilize national efforts to combat the epidemic in the shortest possible time, the economic and social costs to be faced are unavoidable.

We still have to face many unknown issues, for example, these large-scale floating employment population in the city after the Spring Festival will bring what kind of impact? Should more be done to prevent the risk of transmission of the epidemic that may arise from the process of migrant workers returning to their cities for employment? After all, Beijing is likely to have nearly 8M returnees, Shanghai is estimated to have more than 9M, Shenzhen nearly 10m, Guangdong has more than 20m and the country has hundreds of millions. How much more will it cost us in manpower, Material and capital?

We need to reflect on the negative pressure that the epidemic has generated in the course of the most widespread spread of population mobility, and whether we also need to reflect on what institutional barriers have not been broken in recent years in controlling the pressure of population mobility, that we pay such a huge economic and social cost.

It's time to rethink the city's residency policy

China is the country with the largest floating population in the world. This, of course, is due to China's large population, but the more important reason is that the reform of the household registration system has lagged behind, resulting in the employment and settlement of the population amphibious behavior. The most typical example of the annual expansion of population mobility is the Spring Festival travel rush.

China has long enjoyed what is known as a demographic dividend, in which it takes advantage of migrant employment while limiting or limiting the number of migrants who can settle in cities and easing the pressure on local governments to pay for public services. Although the central government has recently adopted a series of policy measures, the hope is that cities with larger populations will be able to relax or relax restrictions on immigration. But for a variety of reasons of interest, in the area of population inflow, not only in the big cities, even in small towns also difficult to implement.

It can be said that if we had not encountered such a major epidemic, may not have expected to pay such a huge cost, immediate fiscal expenditure and future economic development will bring huge risks and burdens. After the SARS epidemic 17 years ago and the COVID-19 epidemic, should we reflect on how to strengthen urban governance fundamentally through relevant reform policies, to avoid a nationwide chain reaction of one city's problems? To prevent national crises arising from local crises or population movements?

It is time to rethink the policy of settling down in cities. It can be assumed that if the problem of permanent migration into urban employment is solved, even if it is not in the main urban area of a large city, but in the surrounding small cities and towns, how much less social pressure would there be for mobility? How much less of a burden would it be to deal with other social crises that might arise from local epidemics? How much less pressure will it put on the rest of the country? It should be said that no matter from the local or national set out, will greatly reduce the economic and social costs.

The so-called"come out to mix, eventually want to return". As a result of various interests and institutional reasons, population inflow areas are reluctant to implement the policy of the reform of the household registration system. For the areas of population inflow, if migrant workers can be resettled from the perspective of urbanization and the relaxation of residency restrictions, even if the epidemic has already occurred, there is no doubt that it will also fundamentally reduce the social risks associated with large-scale population movements.

Need to see, if we do not at this time to reflect on the central government's long-standing emphasis on the implementation of the reform policies of the household registration system, or stand in the interests of the region to carry out various negative resistance, sooner or later, then, a social crisis like this will occur. The economic and social costs will certainly exceed the costs of implementing the household reform and citizenization policies at an early date. This is not only a city and a region's problem, but also a national problem.

At this time of crisis, we should reflect not on how to cure a headache or a foot-ache, but on the lessons learned from the spread of this massive epidemic, we will accelerate the reform of the household registration system and the citizenization of the migrant population, and solve the social problems caused by large-scale population movements. Only stabilizing and reducing the scale of population movements will significantly reduce the risk of outbreaks and crises.

(the writer is chief economist at the Center for Urban and small-town reform and development in China. Editor: Zhu Tao.)
